40:09.451 --> 40:11.578
Are we going jaboozin, or
what’s happening?

40:11.619 --> 40:12.704
We’re jaboozin!

40:12.746 --> 40:14.122
Okay.

40:14.164 --> 40:15.373
[laughing]

40:22.964 --> 40:25.383
Is there a drink holder?

40:33.433 --> 40:36.019
-Is it?
-My pectorals.

40:39.689 --> 40:41.107
Oh, my God, I’m ready for bed.

41:09.386 --> 41:13.306
If I pull my shorts up too high
then I’ll get camel-toe, so...

41:13.348 --> 41:15.016
[laughing]

41:15.058 --> 41:16.351
-Hey, good morning.
-How are you?

41:16.393 --> 41:17.686
I see you’re ready.

41:17.727 --> 41:18.853
Looks like
the weather’s cooperating.

41:18.895 --> 41:19.854
Time to go.

41:19.896 --> 41:21.147
Do you still wanna go stern to,

41:21.189 --> 41:22.357
or do you wanna swing
your bow over?

41:22.399 --> 41:23.483
Stern-out.

41:23.525 --> 41:24.818
Sure, and then
I’ll tell the guys...

41:24.859 --> 41:26.152
-Location, distances.
-Yeah.

41:26.194 --> 41:27.529
-Location, distances.
-All right, cool.

41:27.570 --> 41:29.197
Thanks, Cap.

41:29.239 --> 41:30.532
Deck crew, what’s your location?

41:30.573 --> 41:31.908
On the dock.

41:35.036 --> 41:38.832
Okay, so, Courtney, you’re
gonna be on the bow with Jason.

41:38.873 --> 41:40.250
When you’re bringing the
spring in, like,

41:40.291 --> 41:42.252
and you single out, get it
in as soon as possible.

41:42.293 --> 41:44.379
Yeah, yeah, you
have to get it in.

41:44.421 --> 41:45.630
-Yeah.
-So, Jason.

41:45.672 --> 41:47.382
When the bow has
cleared the dolphins,

41:47.424 --> 41:48.633
you say "clear to swing."

41:48.675 --> 41:50.385
So, you’re gonna be
on the stern with me.

41:50.427 --> 41:52.137
What did you say about
the single-up thing?

41:52.178 --> 41:55.056
-The brace lines will go first.
-Yeah.

41:55.098 --> 41:58.143
<i>All crew,</i>
<i>we’re ready to depart.</i>

41:58.184 --> 42:00.228
We can free up all the lines.

42:00.270 --> 42:02.897
<i>-Bring ’em all in.</i>
<i>-Copy that, Captain.</i>

42:02.939 --> 42:04.149
Mzi, please join
me on the stern.

42:04.190 --> 42:05.400
All right.

42:05.442 --> 42:07.152
I’m so happy to be back,
like, as a deckhand.

42:07.193 --> 42:09.821
And I’m glad that these lines
are a lot smaller than

42:09.863 --> 42:11.406
my last boat, because
I’m hoping

42:11.448 --> 42:14.034
that it’ll be a lot easier now,
because these are smaller.

42:14.075 --> 42:15.910
So, you know when you,
like, learn

42:15.952 --> 42:17.537
with something
harder or bigger...

42:21.207 --> 42:23.376
Captain, that’s all
lines off the bow.

42:23.418 --> 42:24.836
Right, Captain,
that’s all lines on deck.

42:24.878 --> 42:26.504
Great!
Here we go.

42:31.509 --> 42:34.637
Storm, distances.
Storm, distances.

42:34.679 --> 42:35.680
<i>Copy that.</i>

42:35.722 --> 42:38.933
Five meters starboard quarter.

42:38.975 --> 42:41.770
[garbled radio chatter]

42:41.811 --> 42:43.730
Ten meters,
starboard quarter.

42:43.772 --> 42:45.815
You know, Storm, you’re not
coming through on my radio,

42:45.857 --> 42:47.609
so press the mic
and then talk.

42:47.650 --> 42:49.736
Thirty meters [garbled
radio chatter] quarter.

42:49.778 --> 42:52.614
Hey, Jason, can I swing?

42:52.655 --> 42:54.324
Yeah.

42:56.159 --> 42:59.120
Thirty [garbled radio chatter]
meters starboard quarter.

42:59.162 --> 43:00.872
Storm, again, press the mic
and then talk.

43:00.914 --> 43:02.457
<i>I do not hear your distances.</i>

43:02.499 --> 43:04.584
Six meters [garbled
radio chatter] stern.

43:04.626 --> 43:06.044
I don’t hear Storm.

43:06.086 --> 43:09.297
Three meters to V4 off your
[garbled radio chatter].

43:09.339 --> 43:12.634
Kick forward.
Kick forward.

43:12.676 --> 43:14.636
Storm, can’t hear.

43:14.678 --> 43:17.055
Two meters to V4 [garbled
radio chatter] quarter.

43:17.097 --> 43:20.141
And Storm, again, press
your mic and then talk.

43:20.183 --> 43:21.851
Ugh!
We’re gonna hit.

43:21.893 --> 43:26.940
One meter...
oh!

43:26.981 --> 43:29.526
Next, on "Below Deck Med"...

43:29.567 --> 43:30.902
[cheering]

43:30.944 --> 43:32.862
Yay, they’re having fun.

43:35.699 --> 43:37.242
Getting back together

43:37.283 --> 43:40.328
with my ex,
Dave is going to be upset.

43:41.830 --> 43:43.081
I don’t know what runs through

43:43.123 --> 43:44.582
Dave’s head at
the best of times.

43:46.710 --> 43:47.836
Something is definitely wrong.

43:47.877 --> 43:49.170
Kyle?

43:49.212 --> 43:51.297
It’s, like, literally
paining so much.

43:51.339 --> 43:53.341
I need to get him help quickly.

43:56.261 --> 43:57.804
-Seriously, this wind.
-Ooh!

43:57.846 --> 43:59.055
Uh-oh.

43:59.097 --> 44:00.890
Carlos, I can’t get the
stabilizers on.

44:00.932 --> 44:03.601
Oh, not again.

44:03.643 --> 44:05.020
Hang on, everybody.

44:05.895 --> 44:07.897
<i>Hang on, hang on.</i>
